{code:php}
$packedArray = MongoDB\BSON\PackedArray::fromPHP([1, 2, 3]);
var_dump($packedArray->toPHP(['root' => 'bson']));
{code}

This produces the following output:

{noformat}
object(MongoDB\BSON\Document)#2 (1) {
  ["data"]=>
  string(36) "GgAAABAwAAEAAAAQMQACAAAAEDIAAwAAAAA="
}
{noformat}

I'll concede that the type map doesn't make much sense on its own, although the above "root" option could certainly accompany a more complex type map and the output would be the same.

I would have expected the result to be a PackedArray, although this may be intentional since we're interpreting the PackedArray as a root document. In that case, this behavior may be closely related to PHPC-2219.

To allow users to use {{BSON\PackedArray}} instances like array, the class should implement functionality similar to {{ArrayAccess}}. This would allow the following uses:

{code}
// Before
$packedArray->get(0);
// After
$packedArray[0];

// Before
$packedArray->has(0);
// After
isset($packedArray[0]);
{code}

Since instances of the class are a read-only, the following are expected to throw:
{code}
$packedArray[0] = 'foo';
$packedArray[] = 'foo';
unset($packedArray[0]);
{code}

Accessing invalid offsets should also throw (e.g. string offsets, negative values, out-of-bounds keys):
{code}
$packedArray['foo'];
$packedArray[-1];
{code}

To allow users to use {{BSON\Document}} instances like a standard PHP array or object, the class should implement functionality similar to {{ArrayAccess}} and magic accessors. This would allow the following uses:

{code}
// Before
$document->get('foo');
// After
$document['foo'];
$document->foo;

// Before
$document->has('foo');
// After
isset($document['foo']);
isset($document->foo);
{code}

Since instances of the class are a read-only, the following are expected to throw:
{code}
$document['foo'] = 'foo';
$document->foo = 'foo';
$document[] = 'foo';
unset($document['foo']);
unset($document->foo);
{code}

Accessing non-existing keys should throw the same way as {{Document::get}} does.

When dealing with a class that implements the {{\_\_get}} and {{\_\_isset}} magic methods, the null coalesce operator will generally not invoke {{\_\_get}} if {{\_\_isset}} already returns {{false}}: https://3v4l.org/GBCfS.

However, the BSON {{Document}} and {{PackedArray}} classes behave differently, in that using the coalesce operator still results in an exception:

{code}
$document = MongoDB\BSON\Document::fromPHP([]);

var_dump(isset($document->foo));
var_dump($document->foo ?? 'fallback');
{code}

This code outputs the following:
{noformat}
bool(false)

Fatal error: Uncaught MongoDB\Driver\Exception\RuntimeException: Could not find key "foo" in BSON document in /Users/alcaeus/Code/mongodb/mongo-php-driver/tests/bson/bson-document-property-access-002.php:8
{noformat}

For consistency, the {{read_property}} and {{read_dimension}} handlers should not throw when the coalesce operator is used.

The method [{{MongoDB\BSON\UTCDateTime::toDateTime()}}|https://www.php.net/manual/en/mongodb-bson-utcdatetime.todatetime.php] returns a mutable {{DateTime}} instance. The community pushes for using ImmutableDateTime as much as possible.
 * [https://www.reddit.com/r/PHP/comments/w7v4pb/deprecating_the_mutable_datetime_class/] 
 * [https://blog.devgenius.io/stop-using-datetime-in-php-66df3d731875]
 * [https://www.nikolaposa.in.rs/blog/2019/07/01/stop-using-datetime/]

 

Currently, to get a DateTimeImmutable object from an UTCDateTime, developers have to do that:
{code:java}
$date = new UTCDateTime();
$dateTime = ImmutableDateTime::fromMutable($date->toDateTime());{code}
Proposed implementations:

Add a method:
{code:java}
$dateTime = $date->toDateTimeImmutable();{code}
Add a argument:
{code:java}
$dateTime = $date->toDateTime(mutable: false);{code}
We can change the default value of mutable in 2.0 to return an immutable object by default. This change can be announced by deprecating not-passing an argument to the method.

